randoop.types

Class ParameterizedType

  • java.lang.Object
    • randoop.types.GeneralType
      • randoop.types.ConcreteType
        • randoop.types.ParameterizedType

  • public class ParameterizedType
extends ConcreteType
    Represents a parameterized type as a generic class instantiated with concrete type arguments.

    Note that ParameterizedType is an interface that can represent either a parameterized type in the sense meant here, or a generic class. Conversion to this type from this and other Type interfaces is handled by GeneralType.forType(java.lang.reflect.Type).

      • isAssignableFrom

        public boolean isAssignableFrom(ConcreteType sourceType)
        Indicates whether a value of a ConcreteType can be assigned to a variable of this type: Variablethis = Expressionsourcetype. In other words, this is a legal assignment. Based on the definition of assignment context in section 5.2 of the JDK 8 Java Language Specification a value of one type is assignable to a variable of another type if the first type can be converted to the second by
        • an identity conversion,
        • a widening primitive conversion,
        • a widening reference conversion,
        • a boxing conversion, and
        • an unboxing conversion possibly followed by a widening conversion.
        And, if after all those conversions, the type is a raw type, an unchecked conversion may occur.

        When implementing this method, be aware that the method Class.isAssignableFrom(Class) checks identity and reference conversions, and does a comparison of raw types for parameterized types. The method PrimitiveTypes.isAssignable(Class, Class) checks identity and primitive widening for primitive types. Tests for assignability to a parameterized type: can the given concrete type be assigned to this parameterized type.

        A ConcreteType is assignable to a parameterized type via identity, widening reference conversion, or unchecked conversion from raw type. The method Class.isAssignableFrom(Class) checks widening reference conversion, but with parameterized types it is also necessary to check type arguments. Since a widening reference conversion (JLS, section 5.1.5) exists from type S to type T if S is a subtype of T, this method calls isSubtypeOf(ConcreteType) to test the subtype relation.

        Overrides:
        isAssignableFrom in class ConcreteType
        Parameters:
        sourceType - the type to test for assignability
        Returns:
        true if this type can be assigned from the source type, and false otherwise

      • isSubtypeOf

        public boolean isSubtypeOf(ConcreteType type)
                    throws RandoopTypeException
        Test whether this type is a subtype of the given type according to transitive closure of definition of the direct supertype relation in section 4.10.2 of JLS for JavaSE 8. Only checks reference types. Handles specific cases of supertypes of a parameterized type C<T1,...,Tn> instantiating the generic type C<F1,...,Fn> by substitution θ =[F1/T1,...,Fn] for which direct supertypes are:
        1. D<U1θ,...,Ukθ> where D<U1,...,Uk> is a supertype of C<F1,...,Fn>.
        2. C<S1,...,Sn> where Si contains Ti (JLS section 4.5.1).
        3. The rawtype C.
        4. Object if generic form is interface with no interfaces as supertypes.
        Note that the full definition of the contains relation in the second clause involves wildcards, which are not currently implemented, and so the relation reduces to equality on the parameter bounds. (Tested using GenericClassType.equals(Object).)
        Overrides:
        isSubtypeOf in class GeneralType
        Parameters:
        type - the possible supertype
        Returns:
        true if this type is a subtype of the given type, false otherwise
        Throws:
        RandoopTypeException
        See Also:
        ConcreteType.isAssignableFrom(ConcreteType), isSubtypeOf(ConcreteType)
